Since both versions fail with `null`, the placeholder must be handling a different non-object case. Looking at `typeof null === 'object'` in JavaScript - `null` IS typeof 'object'! So the outer check `if (typeof b !== 'object')` wouldn't catch `null`.

The inner check `if (typeof b !== 'object') {` inside would also be redundant... unless the outer block has `b = {};` and the inner check is something else entirely.

